# How to Make an A4 Rectangle from a Square (Origami Guide)

## Overview

This origami construction shows how to transform any square sheet of paper into a perfect A4 rectangle, following the ISO 216 standard proportion (1 : √2).

Unlike traditional origami models, this is a geometric construction that is extremely useful for paper resizing, printing alignment, and mathematical exploration using paper folding techniques.

## What is the A4 Proportion?

The A4 format follows a unique aspect ratio defined by the ISO 216 standard:

- Ratio: 1 : √2 (approximately 1 : 1.414)
- This ratio allows a sheet to be folded in half while preserving proportions

This is why all A-series paper sizes (A0, A1, A2, A3, A4, etc.) maintain the same shape when scaled.

## Difficulty

Beginner to Intermediate

While the folds themselves are simple, precision is important to achieve the exact mathematical proportion.

## Tips for Accuracy

- Use thin paper for better precision
- Align edges carefully before creasing
- Repeat folds lightly before committing
- Small errors can affect the final proportion

## Applications

This construction is useful for:

- Creating A4 sheets from square paper
- Understanding geometric constructions
- Teaching mathematical concepts visually
- Origami design and paper engineering

## Mathematical Insight

This model is a great demonstration of how origami can be used as a tool for geometric construction.

By using folds instead of measurements, it is possible to accurately recreate irrational ratios like √2 with surprising precision.
